Over the weekend I taught two seminars covering the bodylock pass, and spotlighted a majority of the time, the ending will come down to 3 very distinct leg scenarios when controlling your opponent. These endings also come from shin pinning, smash passing, and of course are the core of nearside underhook passing. 
In this clip, I used one such ending: 

This came from a shin pin that slipped into an over/under. 
Then…

➡️ when opponent hipped away, I stepped over the legs and began climbing the body with head up the middle

➡️ I used the nearside underhook as he “put” me into 1/2 butterfly guard. We know that when there is a butterfly hook from the bottom, we should (not mandatory, but safer) put a butterfly hook on top 

➡️I pushed the far knee down and he turned on his side, but now I’m nearly mounted…. 

➡️ I used the principle of controlling his arm through HIS grip to finally mount. 

➡️and finally, pulling the wrist up vs a stiff arm while mounted to maintain mount. 

This competition was from circa 2012 🤗. 
Btw, the history of the bodylock pass may surprise you… 🧐🤔

I love seeing the Nearside Underhook becoming one of the mainstream passing tools! I’ve been preaching this method for nearly 20 years now and so excited to see some of the best in the World using it! 
Here are 3 very recent examples of exceptionally talented individuals using it brilliantly on their opposition. Those that invest time in learning it will maul through guards that once seemed problematic. Those that don’t know… well…prepared to be mauled. :)

Example 1: Tainan Dalpra vs Isaque Bahiense
Example 2 Johnatha Alves vs Elijah Dorsey
Example 3: Stephen Martinez vs Calon Sabino

Go get a @flograppling membership if you don’t have it, so that you can study it! 

The Nearside Undertook (NSU) will change your passing game… PERIOD. 
I put out a simple instructional on this back in 2010, and have a pretty intensive section in my instructional: BODYLOCK THE WORLD…. You can see the ESSENTIALS on my latest YouTube channel.

Would you like me to put out a complete Nearside Underhook Masterclass - using both GI and No Gi?…

#ifyouknowyouknow #whatyoudontknowyoudontknow

21 years ago today. 
Most of us will be black belts longer than any other belt… 
- so be patient, 
- be attentive, 
- keep your mind active on and off of the mat, 
- win training partners (no, no one HAS to train with you… you must win them) 
- slow down
- strive for flawless technique and the understanding of not only HOW, but WHEN and WHY. 
- and among other things… NEVER STOP TRAINING… 
Jiu Jitsu will be one of the most incredible journeys of your life, and one of the greatest gifts that you can give both to yourself and those around you! 

So grateful to @renzograciebjj for all of your guidance and teaching. Without your approach, I would not have been half of the martial artist that I am today! 🙏🏼🙏🏼🙏🏼

I see students, and not only newer students, I’ve seen very talented wrestlers also placing the side of their face or chin on the mat when their body is the prone (facing down) position.  AVOID THIS! NOT ONLY IS IT DANGEROUS, YOU WILL LOSE THE POWER OF YOUR BACK.  COACHES… if you see this, immediately correct it and teach your students to base on essentially their forehead or side of their forehead (with chin tucked). This will keep you safe if your hips get put over your head…. It will also give you the room to work and give you the benefit of being able to engage your back while you work underneath your torso.  Simple tip, but will keep you safe and give you balance and leverage. 

#jiujitsutips #bjj #jiujitsulifestyle #neckandspinesafety #jiujitsu101 #grapplingsafety

What an experience! It was a such an honor to host my teacher, Renzo Gracie yesterday. For me, getting to see all of my students light up from his presence and method of teaching (and storytelling of course) was exceptionally special. It also reminded me of how truly lucky I was to decide to brave the rickety old elevator on 27th street way back in September of 1996 on my way up to my first class.  His method of teaching was the foundation that set all of us up that came from that generation to systematize our jiu jitsu and find relationships and commonalities in the tools used in the art to make learning, understanding and application so much easier. 🚀🚀🔥

Thank you to all of you who were able to attend! 🙏🏼

What a special day! …oh yes, and I was promoted to 5th degree 🥋😬.
